The habitual residence of a child corresponds to the place which reflects some degree of integration by the child in a social and family environment; it is not necessary for a child to be fully integrated before becoming habitually resident in a place. When looking at the degree of integration of the child in a social and family environment in the country concerned, the court will look at numerous factors, “including the reasons for the family's stay in the country in question”

